d as belonging together. Evolutionism regarded magic as quintessentially "unmodern." Although psychologists and romantic artists have sometimes declared magic to be a human universal, few modern scholars in the humanities and social sciences have studied how modern culture and institutions incorporated and even produced magic. This book is the first to adopt a comparative approach to the study of magic as something that has a place in modernity, and that helped to constitute modern society at local and global levels. The essays in this collection contribute to recent discussions in anthropology, cultural studies, comparative literature, history, and sociology that increasingly question the extent to which modern self-conceptions are accurate reflections of a state of affairs in the world rather than cultural interventions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aDubois, Laurent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeschiere, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonwana, Alcinda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, Birgit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, Birgit, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPels, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPels, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPrakashw, Gyan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShaw, Rosalind, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaussig, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVerrips, 